body: I think this can be closed. @rGitcy feel free to add more questions (and re-open) if you think the answer provided does not add up.
Maybe the last operator is div, not mul, according to the chain rule.

> Maybe the last operator is div, not mul, according to the chain rule.

i argee with you!

> I think this can be closed. @rGitcy feel free to add more questions (and re-open) if you think the answer provided does not add up.

thx. But i think the last operator is div, not mul according to the differentiation formulas of erf. please check it.

forward graph:

x->erf->output

output = erf(x)

backward graph:

gradient_of_output -> erf_grad -> gradient_of_x

chain rule
gradient_of_x = gradient_of_output * erf_grad(x)

> forward graph:
> 
> x->erf->output
> 
> output = erf(x)
> 
> backward graph:
> 
> gradient_of_output -> erf_grad -> gradient_of_x
> 
> chain rule gradient_of_x = gradient_of_output * erf_grad(x)

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/22522161/199135980-2c58fb82-00ed-44d4-93b4-189f81c211a4.png)
The formula is  y=erf(x), dy/dx= (2/sqrt(pi)) * (e^(-(x*x))), not dx/dy

> forward graph:
> 
> x->erf->output
> 
> output = erf(x)
> 
> backward graph:
> 
> gradient_of_output -> erf_grad -> gradient_of_x
> 
> chain rule gradient_of_x = gradient_of_output * erf_grad(x)

The computation should be rule gradient_of_output = gradient_of_input * erf_grad(x) according to the differentiation formulas of erf.

issue.body:
### Describe the documentation issue

#13512 
forward graph:

x->erf->output

output = erf(x)

backward graph:

gradient_of_output (dy) -> erf_grad -> gradient_of_input（dx）

The computation should be rule gradient_of_output = gradient_of_input * erf_grad(x) according to the differentiation formulas of erf.

### Page / URL

_No response_

body:
> @baijumeswani @mattetti please check it again!

It's not to compute dx, let C is cost function, so gradient(x) is dC/dx and gradient(y) is dC/dy.

gradient(x) = dC/dx = (dC/dy)*f' = gradient(y)*f'.
